<taxonomicName id="013DA34086BFD936C7EC6002935D4BB0" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. ishiharai" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="ishiharai">
<emphasis id="E6F70190A4DA51505E9547F65BCB7849" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. ishiharai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="46E5C1F705FE03CF58BAE89669C79CFC" captionStart="Figure 35" captionStartId="F35" captionText="Figure 35. Diagnostic characters of Pyrrhalta ishiharai Kimoto A antenna, male B antenna, female C aedeagus, dorsal view D ditto, lateral view E apex of tibia of middle leg, male F abdominal ventrite VIII G spermatheca H tarsi of middle leg, male I abdominal ventrite V, female J abdominal ventrite V, male K gonocoxae." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure35" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545565" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">35K</figureCitation>
))
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5F5EFDB26CBFC685FA9342D999BB57C9" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="host">
<paragraph id="8A91EEA9CB37A8E028D7952EE45F1C0B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Host plant.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="061449A92318A5410066C90EAC99CD51" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Larvae and adults feed on flowers of 
<taxonomicName id="7DDF156397A02552DC13826F4FEA4C1F" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="Meliosma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Meliosma rhoifolia" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="rhoifolia">
<emphasis id="46FF4288157183B08145B31E7303FBEA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Meliosma rhoifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Maxim. (
<taxonomicName id="83E95934A42D076121E4C056BA440C9C" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Sabiaceae" genus="Meliosma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Sapindales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="family">Sabiaceae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DC4DF1AC210BA853320390B3F98EAA0F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="64E7AC89014FC933B3BB50EDDCDF9925" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4CEC8DB29A7AEC59A4A0E897E1841B50" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
One female was collected on flowers of the host plant (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="EB69331822B57128034E2575C682B3F1" captionStart="Figure 37" captionStartId="F37" captionText="Figure 37. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta wulaiensis sp. nov. on host plant A egg B third-instar larva C mature larva D pupa E adult F adults: P. wulaiensis sp. nov. (left) and P. ishiharai (right)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure37" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545567" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">37E</figureCitation>
) July 8, 2011 in Wulai, northern Taiwan by Mr Mei-Hua Tsou. The female deposited eggs (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="64FC11FB1964C71EEF55C0C682AC1BF1" captionStart="Figure 37" captionStartId="F37" captionText="Figure 37. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta wulaiensis sp. nov. on host plant A egg B third-instar larva C mature larva D pupa E adult F adults: P. wulaiensis sp. nov. (left) and P. ishiharai (right)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure37" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545567" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">37A</figureCitation>
) singly on flowers July 12. Larvae hatched in seven days. The larvae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="3626EDB8D27BE9D9D42AAE26D2B3D6F3" captionStart="Figure 37" captionStartId="F37" captionText="Figure 37. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta wulaiensis sp. nov. on host plant A egg B third-instar larva C mature larva D pupa E adult F adults: P. wulaiensis sp. nov. (left) and P. ishiharai (right)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure37" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545567" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">37B</figureCitation>
) fed on flowers and the larval duration was eleven days. mature larvae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="AEB4FA16F583DA3B48C1D40AEEA134C1" captionStart="Figure 37" captionStartId="F37" captionText="Figure 37. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta wulaiensis sp. nov. on host plant A egg B third-instar larva C mature larva D pupa E adult F adults: P. wulaiensis sp. nov. (left) and P. ishiharai (right)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure37" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545567" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">37C</figureCitation>
) burrowed into soil and built underground chambers for pupation. Duration of the pupal stage (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E5D8C2A832DA98BBA59D071500721BC9" captionStart="Figure 37" captionStartId="F37" captionText="Figure 37. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta wulaiensis sp. nov. on host plant A egg B third-instar larva C mature larva D pupa E adult F adults: P. wulaiensis sp. nov. (left) and P. ishiharai (right)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure37" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545567" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">37D</figureCitation>
) was eight days.
</paragraph>
<caption id="C655954E8424A51447320EF172D765DD" doi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure37" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545567" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" start="Figure 37" startId="F37">
